---
/**
 * Buckeye Personal Injury Attorneys — Location Page
 * HQ office. Watson Rd & Yuma Rd intersection. Teravalis growth corridor.
 */

import PracticeAreaLayout from '../layouts/PracticeAreaLayout.astro';
import { getLocalBusinessSchema } from '../utils/schema';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How long do I have to file a personal injury claim in Buckeye?',
    answer: 'Arizona\'s statute of limitations gives you two years from the date of your injury to file a personal injury lawsuit. Waiting too long means losing your right to recover compensation entirely. Talk to an attorney as soon as possible so evidence doesn\'t disappear.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What should I do after a car crash on Watson Road or MC 85?',
    answer: 'Call 911 first. Get medical attention even if you feel fine. Take photos of the scene, vehicle damage, and any road conditions. Exchange insurance info with the other driver. Then call our Buckeye office before giving a recorded statement to any insurance company.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I need a lawyer for a minor car crash in Buckeye?',
    answer: 'Even "minor" crashes can cause injuries that show up days later. Soft tissue damage, concussions, and herniated discs don\'t always present immediately. An attorney can protect your rights while you focus on getting better. Our consultation is free, so there\'s no risk in asking.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much does it cost to hire AZ Law Now in Buckeye?',
    answer: 'Nothing upfront. We work on contingency, which means you don\'t pay us unless we recover money for you. No hourly fees, no retainer. If we don\'t win your case, you don\'t owe us a dime.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What types of cases does your Buckeye office handle?',
    answer: 'Car crashes, truck crashes, motorcycle crashes, pedestrian injuries, bicycle crashes, slip and fall incidents, wrongful death, elder abuse, nursing home abuse, medical negligence, school bus crashes, and dog bites. If someone else\'s negligence caused your injury in Buckeye, we want to hear about it.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How much is my Buckeye injury case worth?',
    answer: 'Every case is different. Your compensation depends on medical bills, lost wages, pain and suffering, and how the injury affects your daily life. We evaluate all of that during your free consultation and give you a straight answer about what we think your case is worth.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Will my case go to trial?',
    answer: 'Most personal injury cases settle before trial. But insurance companies need to know you\'re willing to go the distance. Our litigation team prepares every case as if it\'s going to a courtroom. That preparation is what gets better settlement offers.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I still recover compensation if I was partially at fault?',
    answer: 'Arizona follows a comparative fault rule. You can still recover compensation even if you were partially responsible for the crash. Your award gets reduced by your percentage of fault. So if you\'re 20% at fault and your damages total $100,000, you\'d recover $80,000.',
  },
];

const localSchema = getLocalBusinessSchema('Buckeye', 'buckeye');
---

<PracticeAreaLayout
  title="Buckeye Personal Injury Attorneys"
  description="Buckeye injury attorneys at AZ Law Now. HQ office on Watson Rd. Car crashes, truck crashes, wrongful death. Free consultation. Call (602) 654-0202."
  canonical="/buckeye/"
  practiceArea="Buckeye Personal Injury Attorneys"
  heroTitle="Buckeye Injury Attorneys Serving the West Valley's Fastest-Growing City"
  heroSubtitle="Buckeye injury attorneys serving the West Valley's fastest-growing city. Our headquarters is here because this is home."
  faqs={faqs}
  schema={localSchema}
>
  <p>
    Buckeye isn't just where we work. It's where we built our firm. Our headquarters sits right here in the heart of the West Valley, and we've watched this city grow from a quiet agricultural town into one of the fastest-growing communities in the country.
  </p>

  <p>
    With a population surging past 124,630 and the Teravalis master-planned community bringing thousands more families west, Buckeye's roads are busier than ever. Watson Road, Yuma Road, MC 85, and the I-10 corridor see more traffic every month. More traffic means more crashes. More crashes mean more people who need real legal help.
  </p>

  <h2>Why a Buckeye-Based Injury Firm Matters</h2>

  <p>
    We know the Watson Road and Yuma Road intersection. We know where MC 85 narrows and where construction zones create hazards near Teravalis. We've handled crashes at Verrado Way and along the I-10 frontage roads. That local knowledge isn't something a Phoenix firm can fake.
  </p>

  <p>
    When Brendan investigates your crash scene, he's not pulling up a map for the first time. He already knows the roads, the traffic patterns, and the problem intersections. That head start matters when building a case.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Buckeye Office</h2>

  <p>
    Our headquarters is located at 530 E. McDowell Rd., Suite 107-160, Buckeye, AZ 85326. We're open Monday through Friday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. Walk-ins are welcome, but calling ahead at <a href="tel:+16026540202">(602) 654-0202</a> helps us prepare for your visit.
  </p>

  <p>
    Buckeye residents can typically get a same-day or next-day consultation. We don't make you wait weeks to find out where your case stands.
  </p>

  <h2>The Team Behind Your Case</h2>

  <p>
    Three people work your case from day one. Brendan Franks investigates the crash scene and builds the evidence file before the insurance company even knows what hit them. Brandon Millam handles the legal strategy and litigation. Stephanie Ramirez keeps you updated so you're never wondering what's happening with your case.
  </p>

  <p>
    That trio model is why we recover results other firms can't. The investigation starts immediately. Not after a retainer. Not after paperwork. Immediately.
  </p>

  <h2>Buckeye's Growth Means More Danger on Local Roads</h2>

  <p>
    Teravalis alone is projected to add 300,000 residents over the next two decades. The infrastructure hasn't caught up yet. Construction zones, temporary lane changes, and unfamiliar drivers create conditions that lead to serious crashes.
  </p>

  <p>
    We're already seeing the consequences. More rear-end collisions on Watson Road. More T-bone crashes at Yuma Road intersections. More commercial truck incidents along I-10 near the Buckeye exits. If you've been hurt in any of these situations, we can help.
  </p>

  <h2>Maricopa County Courthouse Access</h2>

  <p>
    Buckeye injury claims fall under Maricopa County Superior Court jurisdiction. Our litigation team files regularly in the downtown Phoenix courthouse and the Buckeye Justice Court for smaller matters. We know the local judges, the filing procedures, and the timelines. That familiarity keeps your case moving.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Do After a Crash in Buckeye</h2>

  <p>
    First, get safe and call 911. Then document everything you can. Photos of the vehicles, the road, the intersection, and any visible injuries. Get the other driver's insurance information. See a doctor, even if you feel fine. Adrenaline masks pain.
  </p>

  <p>
    Then call us. Don't give a recorded statement to the insurance company first. They'll use your words against you. Let us handle that conversation.
  </p>
</PracticeAreaLayout>
